choices.text:
choosing between the two brutally violent gangs which dominate my street: the Americans and the Taliban.

Like Hamid Karzail who came to power after the American overthrow of the Taliban, in whose name I grew up angry and confused, I’m used to being told that how other people run their countries is nobody else’s business.

But when the hapless Karzai’s latest apology tour – in effect a plea for U.S. largesse – was followed by Barack Obama’s equally unconvincing assurances that the U.S. can deal reliably with an enemy that has kidnapped three American soldiers within 10 days, I began to itch for a fresh excuse to take up arms.

Why does Afghanistan live in such tribal decrepitude, under a mixture of invasions and incumbents whose genuine grievances against each other escalate rapidly into hateful splintered sectarian groups locked in a violent struggle for dominance? How much of all this destruction is really our fault?

In the short 11 years since the U.S.-led invasion, unemployment is still up around 40 percent, illiteracy about 60 percent and most families live on less than $2.50 a day. Five thousand insurgents tactics and night moves have caused about $180 billion in damage and killed around 120 people a week. Afghanistan is a classic case of last-installed postcode-automatic-light-fails syndrome.
